event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting an unsolicited status indication. This is an informational event that indicates an anomaly in a Signaling Gateway application.

  • The application manager ID (appMgrId) indicates the Signaling Gateway process and the Routing Group Number (rgnId) identifies the instance of the affected Signaling Gateway process. The application IDs are:
    • 30 - SgwFtMgr
    • 31 - SgwMtp2
    • 32 - SgwMtp3
    • 33 - SgwIsup
    • 34 - SgwTcap
    • 35 - SgwBicc
  • The AlmCat indicates the alarm category in the Signaling Gateway code:
    • 1 - Protocol
    • 2 - Interface
    • 3 - Internal
    • 4 - Resource
    • 5 - Fault Tolerance
    • 6 - SCCP Error Performance
    • 256 - Protocol Specific
  • The Event, Cause, and EvtParm's information is for Customer Support use only.

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) has received a message indicating that the remote switch identified by the Destination Point Code (dpcId), is reporting a User Part status change (Unavailable). The application manager ID (appMgrId) indicates the affected user part and Routing Group Number (rgnId) identifies the instance of the affected user part. The application IDs are:

  • 33 - SgwIsup
  • 34 - SgwTcap
  • 35 - SgwBicc

The signaling status (SgwStatus) indicates the change received (0x30 for unavailable). Once received, no signaling will be sent to that user part until the remote switch reports the user part is available.

When the user part for either ISUP or BICC is unavailable, all circuits in the associated system groups will be unavailable. Calls will not complete unless there is an alternate route to reach the destination configured in the database.

When the user part for TCAP is unavailable, all TCAP related services would be unavailable, unless the TCAP default routing is configured. In this case AIN and LNP calls will proceed. Calls that requested Calling Name Delivery will be completed without the Calling Name.

Once blocked, the CIC is only available for test calls. If a non-test call is received on this CIC from the remote switch, the remote blocking condition is cleared. The trunk group Common Language Location Identifier (CLLI) name is identified by (CLLIName).

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting an incoming busy CIC has been remotely blocked. The trunk group is identified by (trunkGroupId) and the circuit by (circuitId). The CIC state identified by (SgwCicState) is for Customer Support use only. The application manager ID (appMgrId) identifies the user part and the Routing Group Number (rgnId) identifies the instance of the user part for the affected CIC. The application IDs are:

  • 33 - SgwIsup
  • 35 - SgwBicc

Once blocked, the CIC is only available for test calls. If a non-test call is received on this CIC from the remote switch, the remote blocking condition is cleared. The trunk group Common Language Location Identifier (CLLI) name is identified by (CLLIName).

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting that an MTP link has been locally blocked, resulting in a local processor outage (LPO). This is an indication that local processor outage has raised and sent to the remote switch. LPO refers to the situation when signaling messages cannot be transferred to MTP3 layer and above (ISUP/BICC/SCCP/TCAP). The MTP link is identified by (Mtp3LinkId) and the link blocking status by (LnkBlk). The link blocking status should be set to 1 indicating locally blocked.

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) has received a message indicating that the remote switch identified by the Destination Point Code (dpcId), is reporting a paused condition for the concerned point code. This is an indication that signaling traffic is no longer being exchanged to the DPC. All ISUP and BICC signaling towards the DPC are stopped. Once received, no signaling will be sent to that DPC until the remote switch reports that the DPC has resumed. All circuits in the associated system groups that are configured for this DPC, will be unavailable. Calls will not complete unless there is an alternate route to reach the destination configured in the database.

  • 35 - SgwBicc

Once unblocked, the CIC is available for use (provided the CIC isn't locally blocked). The trunk group Common Language Location Identifier (CLLI) name is identified by (CLLIName).

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting a network resource in currently unavailable. The resource in question is the interface to route to the Destination Point Code (DPC), which is identified by (dpcId). The circuit in question is identified by the trunk group (trunkGroupId), and circuit (circuitId) for the application instance identified by appMgrId and and the Routing Group Number (rgnId). This event will occur when an MTP Pause EVT_MTP3_PAUSE (15035) has been reported and call related messages destined for that DPC are still in progress. The application IDs are:

  • 33 - SgwIsup
  • 35 - SgwBicc
The trunk group Common Language Location Identifier (CLLI) name is identified by (CLLIName).

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting that the application instance identified by (appMgrId) and the Routing Group Number (rgnId), is no longer bound to the MTP3 layer. This event is generated as part of a call control procedure and the application is reporting a loss of connectivity to MTP3. Under normal operations, ISUP and/or BICC layers are bound to the MTP3 layer during initialization. Being bound implies that communications exists between the signaling layers. The circuit that is effected is identified by the trunk group (trunkGroupId), and circuit (circuitId). The application IDs are:

  • 33 - SgwIsup
  • 35 - SgwBicc
The trunk group Common Language Location Identifier (CLLI) name is identified by (CLLIName).

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting that the application instance identified by appMgrId and the Routing Group Number (rgnId), has received a message that is invalid for the configured switch type. Certain countries do not support particular ISUP/BICC messages. As a result, the message is dropped. The circuit effected is identified by the trunk group (trunkGroupId), and circuit (circuitId). The configured switch variants are identified by (valevt), where the switch IDs are:

  • 1 - ITU-T
  • 3 - ANSI'92
  • 9 - Bellcore

The application IDs are:

  • 33 - SgwIsup
  • 35 - SgwBicc
The trunk group Common Language Location Identifier (CLLI) name is identified by (CLLIName).

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting that an MTP link has been locally blocked, resulting in a local processor outage (LPO). This is an indication that local processor outage has raised and sent to the remote switch. LPO refers to the situation when signaling messages cannot be transferred to MTP3 layer and above (ISUP/BICC/SCCP/TCAP). The MTP link is identified by (Mtp3LinkId). There is a matching alarm generated (MTP3 LOCAL PROCESSOR OUTAGE, 15015) at the MTP3 layer for the Signaling Gateway indicating the outage.

event.descr:

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting that it has recovered from local congestion and that it has ended throttling procedures. Congestion recovery at the Signaling Gateway level is caused by the restoration of available Call Manager resources. The criteria for determining the end of congestion is proprietary. By ending local congestion, subsequent release messages sent to the remote switch indicated by the Destination Point Code (dpcId), will no longer include an Automatic Congestion Control (ACC) parameter. The trunk group (trkGrpNum) and circuit (circuitId) identify the current call during which congested ended. Reception of the event indicates that EVT_LOCAL_CONGESTION_LEVEL1 (15206) and EVT_LOCAL_CONGESTION_LEVEL2 (15207) have been cleared. The trunk group Common Language Location Identifier (CLLI) name is identified by (CLLIName).

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting that it has reached congestion level 1 and that it has begun throttling procedures. Congestion at the Signaling Gateway level is caused by the lack of available Call Manager resources. The criteria for determining the congestion is proprietary. Congestion level 1 should result in a reduction in new call originations (load shedding) at the ISUP and/or BICC signaling level. The new call originations from remote nodes (received IAM message) will be released with a cause value indicating switch congestion (42). In addition to the cause value, in the release message, an Automatic Congestion Control (ACC) parameter will be generated to notify the remote switch, identified by the Destination Point Code (dpcId), to begin Automatic Congestion Control procedures (if supported remotely). The trunk group (trkGrpNum) and circuit (circuitId) identify the incoming call that was released. All calls in progress prior to the start of congestion will be completed. The trunk group Common Language Location Identifier (CLLI) name is identified by (CLLIName).

event.descr:
The Signaling Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting that it has reached overload level 1 and that it has begun throttling procedures. Overload level 1 will result in a 50% reduction in new call originations (load shedding) at the ISUP and/or BICC signaling level. New call originations from remote nodes (received IAM message) will be released with a cause value indicating switch congestion (42). In addition to the cause value, in the release message, an Automatic Congestion Control (ACC) parameter will be generated to notify the remote switch to begin congestion control procedures. New call originations from Call Manager, will also be released with cause value 42, which will release the call termination attempt. All calls in progress prior to the start of overload will be completed.

event.descr:
The Signaling SIP Gateway (identified by sgwNum) is reporting that it has reached overload level 1 and that it has begun throttling procedures. Overload level 1 will result in a 50% reduction in new call originations (load shedding) at the SIP signaling level. New call originations from remote nodes (received INVITE message) will be dropped. New call originations from Call Manager, will also be released with cause value 42, which will release the call termination attempt. All calls in progress prior to the start of overload will be completed.
